- Best Practices for High Availability
    i. Design for Failure: Assume that any component of your system can fail at any time and design your system accordingly.
    ii. Implement Health Checks: Regular health checks allow you to detect and respond to issues before they become critical failures.
    iii. Use Multiple Availability Zones: Distribute your system across different data centers to prevent localized failures.
    iv. Practice Chaos Engineering: Intentionally introduce failures to test system resilience.
    v. Implement Circuit Breakers: Prevent cascading failures by quickly cutting off problematic services.
    vi. Use Caching Wisely: Caching can improve availability by reducing load on backend systems.
    vii. Plan for Capacity: Ensure your system can handle both expected and unexpected load increases.